John Edward: Language skills are fundamental for the citizens of the world
Scotland’s independent schools have a track record of academic excellence that has continued in 2018 with another set of extraordinary test results that is reinforced by individual and collective successes in the fields of sport, art, music and other community projects.
With more than 30,000 pupils across Scotland, these centres, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to deliver the best level of service to pupils and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for higher education, for the career of their choice and for their place as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement an adapted curriculum, it is noted that modern languages remain a popular and desired subject in centers.
As Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, the message comes to his head.
If you speak to him in his tongue, it reaches his heart.”
This is a powerful reminder that if you want to build relationships and build trust with people from other countries, you can’t rely solely on English.
If we take into account the recent results of this year’s exams, we can see that languages are at the top of the ranking tables, with the highest pass rates in independent schools.
In total, 68% of students who studied foreign languages obtained an A, the highest grade.
The data, collected from the 74 centers that are part of the SCIS, showed that 72% of students obtained an A in Mandarin, while 72% of those who studied German, 69% of those who studied French and 63% of those who studied Spanish also obtained an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as a fundamental skill that both children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
At present, it is considered that, as a subject, languages are at the same level as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curricula of independent schools and everywhere.
A survey carried out in 2014 by the UK’s Employment and Skills Commission revealed that, of the reasons given by employers for the difficulties they faced in filling jobs, 17% were attributed to a shortage of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly indispensable to prepare young people for their future careers.
Potential job opportunities requiring languages are on the rise, so these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of which career someone chooses, if they have learned a second language, they will have a real edge in the future thanks to a competition like this, which will last a lifetime.
Being able to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will allow that person to automatically get ahead of the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 UK adults in 2013, 75% of them did not speak any foreign language well enough to hold a conversation, and the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage, 15%, was French.
For this reason, investing in language teaching is now important for today’s children.
If they know several languages, especially those in developing economies, children will be equipped to have better opportunities to find quality employment.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Some centres will focus on the more classical modern languages, while others will teach the languages considered most important to the UK by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the interests of a child, in independent schools you can always choose between several languages taught by teaching staff specialized in this subject.
Independent schools in Scotland are dedicated to providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need to succeed, whatever the future holds.
At the moment, it is undeniable that, in a global business environment, languages continue to be of vital importance for the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
Indeed, modern languages must be considered "competences for international communication".
Independent schools will continue to offer these choices, diversity and excellence to Scotland’s young people.
It has to be done.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
