North Korea says 'no chance' it will unilaterally disarm first if it doesn't have confidence
On Saturday, North Korea’s foreign minister informed the United Nations that the continuation of sanctions deepened its distrust of the United States and that there was no possibility of its country unilaterally giving up nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken "important measures of goodwill" over the past year, such as stopping nuclear and missile tests, dismantling nuclear testing facilities and committing to non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"However, we did not receive any similar response from the United States," he said.
“If we don’t have confidence in the United States, we can’t have confidence in our national security, and, in those circumstances, there is no chance that we will unilaterally disarm first.”
Although Ri repeated North Korea’s well-known complaints about Washington’s resistance to a “phased” denuclearization formula that rewards the country as it takes gradual steps, his statement is important, as he did not outright reject unilateral denuclearization, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referenced a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump following the first summit between an active US president and a North Korean leader on June 12 in Singapore, when Kim pledged to work toward the “denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula” and Trump guaranteed the security of North Korea.
North Korea has pursued the official end of the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said Pyongyang must give up its nuclear weapons first.
Washington has also resisted calls to ease international sanctions on North Korea.
“The United States has insisted on denuclearization in the first place and has increased pressure through sanctions in order to achieve its purpose in a coercive manner, including by objecting to a declaration of an end to the war,” Ri said.
“The idea that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a chimera of people who don’t know us.
The problem is that the continuation of sanctions deepens our mistrust.”
Ri made no mention of plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, announced loud and clear by the U.S. leader at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings held between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae over the past five months, adding: “If South Korea had been the party interested in denuclearization instead of the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not be in such a stalemate.”
Even so, the tone of Ri’s speech was radically different from last year’s speech, when he told the U.N. General Assembly that it was inevitable to direct North Korea’s missiles toward U.S. soil after “evil president” Trump, on a suicide mission, called Kim a “rocket man.”
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea, praised Kim for his courage in moving toward disarmament, but said much remained to be done and that sanctions needed to be continued until North Korea was denuclearized.
On Wednesday, Trump said there was no deadline set for this: “It could take two years, three years or five months, it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia argue that the U.N. Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its progress.
However, as U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo reported to the U.N. Security Council on Thursday, “The imposition of Security Council sanctions must continue vigorously and without breach until we make definitive and fully verified denuclearization a reality.”
The Security Council has unanimously imposed sanctions on North Korea since 2006, in a bid to cut off funding for Pyongyang's ballistic missile and nuclear programmes.
Pompeo spoke with Ri outside the U.N. General Assembly and later said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip did not go well.
He left Pyongyang in July saying progress had been made, but a few hours later, North Korea denounced his "demands were those of a mobster."
In a meeting with Moon earlier this month, North Korea pledged to dismantle a missile site and a nuclear complex if the United States applied “corresponding measures.”
He said Kim had communicated to him that the “corresponding measures” he was seeking were the security guarantees Trump had promised in Singapore and steps toward normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students take a course on how to get enough rest
Thanks to a new course being taught this year at Harvard University, all college students are getting more sleep in an attempt to fight the growing macho culture of studying all night drinking caffeine.
One professor found that students at the world’s number one university often have no idea about basic self-care.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School, and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital designed the course, believed to be the first of its kind in the U.S.
Her motivation to launch the course came after giving a talk about how sleep deprivation affects learning.
“At the end of the course, a girl came up to me and asked me why she just found out about this now, in her senior year.
He said no one had ever told him about the importance of sleep, which surprised me," she told The Telegraph.
The course, taught for the first time this year, explains to students the basics of how good sleep habits contribute to academic and sports performance, as well as improving overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students barely slept during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section, there is an image of a bedroom, where students click on coffee cups, curtains, sneakers and books that inform them of the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of lack of sleep on sports performance and the importance of establishing a bedtime routine.
In another section, participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
Then, a campus icon with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
“We know it’s not going to change student behavior instantly.
However, we believe that they have a right to know, just as anyone has a right to know the health effects of smoking tobacco,” Professor Czeisler added.
He said the culture of pride in “sleep-overs” still exists, adding that modern technology and the increasing pressure on students meant sleep deprivation was a growing problem.
Getting enough sleep and good quality sleep should be the students’ “secret weapon” to combat stress, fatigue and anxiety; even to avoid gaining weight, as sleep deprivation causes the brain to generate a feeling of hunger, which is why they want to eat all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemistry and physics, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending one of his classes the previous year during his freshman year at Harvard.
He noted that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to expand it to the entire campus.
He hopes the next step will be to ask all graduate students to complete a similar program of study before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler's recommendation is that students think about setting an alarm to go to bed and another to wake up, and that they be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" emitted by the screens of electrical appliances and LEDs, which can alter circadian rhythms, so they would end up having trouble falling asleep.
