The National Trust spies on the secret life of bats
This new research, which has been carried out in a Scottish Highland state, attempts to discover how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
The findings are expected to shed more light on the behaviour of the only flying mammals and help guide future conservation activities.
The study, conducted by the National Trust for Scotland, will follow the common bats and sopranos, as well as the riverside Daubenton bat and long-eared browns from the Inverewe Gardens at Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed at strategic locations on the property to track bat activities during the season.
The NHS staff and volunteers will also carry out mobile research with wearable detectors.
Experts will analyze the sounds picked up on the recordings to find out how often bats call and what species do it.
A report and habitat map will then be produced to create a detailed picture of the environment and its behaviour.
Rob Dewar, a nature conservation advisor for NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas of habitat are most important to bats and how each species uses them.
This information will determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as grassland creation and how forests should be maintained for bats and other associated species.
Bat populations in Scotland and the UK have declined considerably over the last century.
They are under threat from construction and development affecting their nests and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and electrical wiring can also pose a risk to them, as can insecticidal papers and other chemical treatments of building materials or attacks from domestic cats.
Bats aren't really blind,
But because of their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes to achieve their goal.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique that locates ants and obstacles in their flight path.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes the subject of bats very seriously.
It has ten trained experts in the field, who are dedicated to conducting regular surveys, nest inspections and, sometimes, rescues.
The organisation has even inaugurated Scotland’s first and only dedicated bat reserve in the state of Threate in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland’s ten bat species.
Property manager David Thompson says it’s the ideal territory for them.
“Here at Threate, we have a fantastic area for bats,” he said.
“We have old buildings, lots of veteran trees and all the right habitat.
However, there is still a lot unknown about bats, so the work we do here and on other properties will help us better understand what they need to develop.”
It emphasizes the importance of checking for bats before carrying out maintenance tasks within the properties, since a breeding colony can be inadvertently destroyed and 400 females and offspring could be killed, which would mean annihilating an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, harass or disturb them, as well as destroy their colonies.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish officer in charge of the Bat Conservation Trust, has encouraged the public to collaborate.
He said: “We still have a lot to learn about bats and many other species that we don’t know how their populations evolve.”
