US-China trade war could benefit Beijing
The first salvos in the U.S.-China trade war were deafening, and while much remains to be done, a break between the countries could benefit Beijing, experts say.
U.S. President Donald Trump issued the first warning earlier this year by placing tariffs on major Chinese exports, such as solar panels, steel and aluminum.
The most significant escalation took place this week with new tariffs affecting $200 billion (<0xC2><0xA3>150 billion) in goods, taxing half of goods entering the United States from China.
On every occasion, Beijing has retaliated with the equivalent of five to 10 percent tariffs on $60 billion worth of U.S. goods.
China has pledged to match U.S. attacks, and the world’s second most powerful economy is unlikely to slacken anytime soon.
Getting Washington to back down would mean giving in to the demands, but publicly submitting to the United States would be too embarrassing for Chinese President Xi Jinping.
Still, experts say that if Beijing plays its cards right, the pressures of the U.S. trade war could positively help China in the long run by reducing interdependence between the two economies.
“The fact that a quick policy decision in Washington or Beijing could create the conditions to start a plummeting economy in either country is actually much more dangerous than viewers have recognized so far,” said Abigail Grace, an Asia-focused research associate at the Center for New American Security.
Syria ready for return of refugees, says foreign minister
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and is seeking help to rebuild a country ravaged by a war that has been raging for more than seven years.
In a speech before the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said the country’s conditions were improving.
"The situation on the ground is now more stable and secure thanks to the progress that has been made in the fight against terrorism," he said.
The government continues to rehabilitate the areas destroyed by the terrorists in an attempt to restore normalcy.
All the conditions for the voluntary return to the country of refugees who had to leave the country due to terrorism and unilateral economic measures affecting their daily lives and livelihoods are already in place.
The UN estimates that since the war began in 2011, more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country.
There are another six million people still living in the country and in need of humanitarian aid.
Al-Moualem acknowledged that the Syrian regime would appreciate help to rebuild the devastated country.
But he also stressed that he would not accept conditional aid or aid from countries that promoted the insurgency.
