Red Tide Update: Decreased Concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee, and Sarasota
The new report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows an overall reduction in red tide concentrations in areas of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, irregular flowering conditions are being reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, suggesting a reduction in concentrations.
Red tide bloom extends approximately 130 miles of coastline from Pinellas County in the north to Lee County in the south.
Irregular plots can be found about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer places compared to last week.
Red tide has also been detected in Pasco County.
During the past week, average concentrations have been reported in Pinellas County and its coast, low-to-high concentrations in Hillsborough County’s coast, background to high concentrations in Manatee County, background to high concentrations in Sarasota County and its coast, background to medium concentrations in Charlotte County, background to high concentrations in Lee County and its coast, and Collier to high concentrations in Lee County and its coast.
Respiratory irritation problems continue to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
There have been no reported respiratory irritation issues in northwest Florida over the past week.
